WEBVTT

00:11.052 --> 00:13.013
Inside,
outside, inside, outside,

00:13.096 --> 00:15.432
inside, outside, inside, outside,

00:15.515 --> 00:17.600
inside, outside, inside, outside...

00:17.684 --> 00:19.561
<i>Having taken Stan hostage,</i>

00:19.853 --> 00:23.398
<i>Oscar and Buster believed they were
on a flight from justice.</i>

00:23.481 --> 00:25.692
- Who is this guy?
- I don't know... inside...

00:25.775 --> 00:27.610
but I don't like
the looks of him... outside...

00:27.694 --> 00:29.738
He's a friend, just saying hi.
What do I do?

00:29.821 --> 00:31.448
Okay, no funny business. Inside...

00:31.531 --> 00:33.324
- Yeah, don't be a hero.
- Outside...

00:33.408 --> 00:37.078
- Do I say hi? What do I do?
- All right, acting natural and stopping

00:37.162 --> 00:39.456
in three, two, one.

00:40.248 --> 00:41.666
Hello.

00:41.750 --> 00:44.377
Ah. Hurt your hand?

00:45.128 --> 00:46.171
Tell him to off.

00:46.254 --> 00:49.007
Yeah, yeah, yeah, to F off,
twinkle toes. Tell him to F off.

00:49.090 --> 00:52.469
Let me handle this. Call the police. Ow!

00:52.552 --> 00:55.263
My son is coming in from Ojai
next Tuesday.

00:55.346 --> 00:57.015
- Ah.
- Leading with the inside.

00:57.098 --> 00:59.726
- Three, two, one.
- Goodbye.

01:00.310 --> 01:03.605
- Call the police.
- Inside, outside, inside, outside...

01:03.688 --> 01:05.899
<i>Now the story of a wealthy family</i>

01:05.982 --> 01:07.984
<i>who lost everything, and the one son</i>

01:08.109 --> 01:10.195
<i>who had no choice
but to keep them all together.</i>

01:16.910 --> 01:18.620
<i>It's </i> Arrested Development.

01:21.790 --> 01:23.958
<i>Fakeblock is gonna change the world.</i>

01:24.042 --> 01:26.336
<i>After George Michael's</i>
<i>girlfriend expressed interest</i>

01:26.419 --> 01:27.921
<i>in seeing his business...</i>

01:28.088 --> 01:30.048
Which reminds me, I'm dying to see it.

01:30.131 --> 01:32.967
<i>- ...he was desperate for a way out.</i>
<i>- </i><i>Why don't you just tell Rebel</i>

01:33.176 --> 01:35.053
- she can't see the company?
- Then she's gonna know

01:35.136 --> 01:37.430
I'm not a tech entrepreneur
named George Maharis.

01:37.514 --> 01:40.225
<i>Fortunately,</i>
<i>his uncle inspired a solution.</i>

01:40.308 --> 01:42.310
- They're paid protestors, boy!
<i>- Unfortunately...</i>

01:42.393 --> 01:44.771
Do you think they could be Anonymous,
like Guy Fawkses?

01:44.854 --> 01:46.856
<i>...Gob had a different interpretation</i>

01:46.940 --> 01:50.151
<i>- of what a Guy Fawkes was.</i>
- Foxy guys.

01:50.235 --> 01:52.112
<i>And when he found</i>
<i>his deception falling apart,</i>

01:52.195 --> 01:54.489
<i>George Michael was in
for a pleasant surprise.</i>

01:54.572 --> 01:56.616
Fakeblock's incredible. Fakeblock is...

01:56.699 --> 01:59.828
- Yeah, Fakeblock is real. Yeah.
<i>- </i><i>And so, he went to thank a cousin</i>

02:00.120 --> 02:03.123
<i>- who was in the middle of a deception.</i>
<i>- I was this close</i>

02:03.206 --> 02:05.041
to telling Rebel the whole truth:
that you fired everyone

02:05.125 --> 02:06.501
months ago, and the thing is a fraud.

02:06.876 --> 02:08.961
Then we open the doors,
and the place is abuzz.

02:09.169 --> 02:11.256
She totally bought it.
She wants to invest now.

02:11.923 --> 02:13.258
I don't know how you did it,
but it was great.

02:13.341 --> 02:14.634
You got people there for the day.

02:15.051 --> 02:16.678
I didn't hire anybody for the day.

02:17.679 --> 02:20.807
Then where did those people come from?
The place was wall-to-wall nerds.

02:20.890 --> 02:22.308
Yeah, this is making sense.

02:22.392 --> 02:25.854
Those people that you saw didn't come in
for the day.

02:26.229 --> 02:27.397
They never left.

02:27.856 --> 02:30.024
Remember when I said I fired everybody?

02:30.191 --> 02:34.904
What I did was, I asked Joan
in HR to fire everybody for me.

02:35.071 --> 02:36.656
Then, so I didn't have to make
two phone calls,

02:36.739 --> 02:38.074
I fired her there on the spot.

02:38.533 --> 02:41.202
- So you fired the person in charge of...
- Firing.

02:41.411 --> 02:44.956
Yes. So, you know,
you fire the person in HR last.

02:45.123 --> 02:46.166
That's the lesson here.

02:46.249 --> 02:48.251
But, hey, this is how you learn
in business, am I right?

02:48.334 --> 02:50.253
We're still somehow paying these people?

02:50.336 --> 02:53.298
Well, we're not paying Joan in HR.
Gotta give me credit for that one.

02:53.381 --> 02:55.466
Well, we're not gonna have
any more credit at all.

02:55.550 --> 02:57.760
That explains why Maeby's
credit cards aren't working.

02:57.969 --> 02:59.137
Maeby's credit cards?

03:00.680 --> 03:03.641
Oh, sorry. The minute I put the teeth in,
I become...

03:03.725 --> 03:05.727
a completely different person.

03:05.810 --> 03:07.896
Speaking of which, there's your solution.

03:07.979 --> 03:09.189
We both have alter egos,

03:09.272 --> 03:11.649
and I think it's about time
we killed them off. What do you say?

03:11.941 --> 03:13.443
George Maharis can have a heart attack.

03:13.526 --> 03:16.362
- Maeby gets hit by a bus.
- Killing off Maeby?

03:16.446 --> 03:18.323
- Yup, see you.
- I know Annette can be forgetful,

03:18.406 --> 03:20.742
but she remembers Maeby
is the dominant personality, right?

03:21.034 --> 03:23.411
Hey, I got a pretty sweet setup here.

03:23.494 --> 03:26.039
Okay?
I finally got rid of my beloved Stan.

03:26.331 --> 03:28.416
He's in the hospital, massive head injury.

03:28.708 --> 03:31.711
Free rent.
New neighbors every six to eight months.

03:32.003 --> 03:34.797
Also, Maeby doesn't even have
a high school diploma.

03:35.215 --> 03:38.092
Not a good move, given the world
my generation is leaving hers.

03:38.176 --> 03:40.720
I'm glad it's easy for you, but me
and George Maharis have the same teeth.

03:41.804 --> 03:43.848
People are gonna figure it out.
If I'm not arrested for fraud,

03:43.932 --> 03:45.058
I'll be in debt for life.

03:45.141 --> 03:48.269
- I'm gonna end up in my old bedroom.
- Yeah. It's six o'clock.

03:48.353 --> 03:50.146
I'm already an hour and a half late
for dinner.

03:50.438 --> 03:54.150
And I'm sorry if I'm repeating myself,
but, uh... Annette,

03:55.026 --> 03:56.527
she like-a the pasta, hmm?

03:57.654 --> 04:00.949
♪ <i>How did you ever find me?</i> ♪

04:01.032 --> 04:03.451
<i>Later that day,</i>
<i>Michael heard a noise coming</i>

04:03.534 --> 04:06.454
<i>from his son's old bedroom
and was surprised</i>

04:06.788 --> 04:09.832
<i>to discover that, this time,</i>
<i>it </i> was <i>his son.</i>

04:10.375 --> 04:13.127
It's you.
What are you doing in your bedroom?

04:13.211 --> 04:15.213
Playing a game
where I just throw the tennis ball

04:15.296 --> 04:18.298
against the wall and try and catch it.
And then if I miss it, I...

04:21.344 --> 04:23.096
Uh, feel pretty bad
and beat myself up,

04:23.179 --> 04:25.390
and then I kind of try
and move past that

04:25.473 --> 04:27.141
and get back on the horse.

04:27.392 --> 04:29.811
Okay. Son, I... I meant,
what... what... what are you doing

04:29.894 --> 04:31.479
back in your old room?

04:31.980 --> 04:33.523
Um... that's just a...

04:33.898 --> 04:35.191
minor regression.

04:35.275 --> 04:37.110
<i>♪ Minor regression ♪</i>

04:37.318 --> 04:40.321
Well, I guess I was actually just trying
to go back to a simpler time.

04:40.571 --> 04:41.698
When I was a young boy and...

04:41.781 --> 04:43.491
all I cared about were simple things

04:43.574 --> 04:45.910
like what does it take
to be a good citizen

04:46.160 --> 04:47.912
and am I gonna be able
to fall asleep tonight,

04:47.996 --> 04:49.289
or am I getting too wound up

04:49.372 --> 04:51.416
- about this good citizen stuff?
- Well, George Michael,

04:51.499 --> 04:53.584
you've always been such
a funny little guy, you know.

04:53.835 --> 04:56.796
Of course it make sense now,
you being a computer genius.

04:56.963 --> 04:59.215
Speaking of which, question: I'm trying

04:59.299 --> 05:01.676
to gather as much capital
as possible to help out Dad,

05:01.759 --> 05:03.469
but I think that they're hiding something.

05:03.553 --> 05:05.680
I mean, they've got secret bookkeeping,
and, um,

05:05.888 --> 05:08.641
came across this file here
called "Gated Community."

05:09.017 --> 05:11.352
Each time I try to print it,
I get this root warning,

05:11.436 --> 05:12.812
- you know...
- Doesn't look

05:12.895 --> 05:14.981
like it came
from a normal printer, actually.

05:15.189 --> 05:17.817
It's not, no, I sent it
to the Smile Maker. It's a dental printer.

05:17.984 --> 05:20.862
Okay. That explains that toothbrush
next to the warning sign.

05:21.070 --> 05:23.156
And you see how they spelled
"byte" without a <i>y.</i>

05:23.448 --> 05:25.074
- No, this is for dentists.
- Listen to you.

05:25.158 --> 05:27.577
This is why you have
a billion-dollar software company

05:27.660 --> 05:29.537
and your old man has to hit "popcorn"
on the microwave

05:29.620 --> 05:31.122
any time I want to heat something up.

05:31.205 --> 05:34.125
- You hit "heat," then hit "time," then...
- Mine does not work that way.

05:34.208 --> 05:37.420
But popcorn sounds good.
Let's go make some of that. Come on.

05:37.587 --> 05:41.424
<i>Unbeknownst to the guys,</i>
<i>and directly over their heads,</i>

05:41.799 --> 05:45.345
<i>Tobias had just experienced
his own snack problems.</i>

05:45.428 --> 05:48.890
I knew it.
Okay. I had nine gummy bears

05:48.973 --> 05:50.141
wrapped in tinfoil here,

05:50.224 --> 05:52.518
and the tinfoil is still here,
but, uh, I'm super confused.

05:52.810 --> 05:55.480
Do we have magic gummy bears
that just get up and walk away?

05:55.563 --> 05:58.149
Yeah, one got up
and walked right into my mouth.

05:58.232 --> 05:59.525
What're you gonna do about it?

05:59.609 --> 06:00.985
<i>And the cramped quarters</i>

06:01.069 --> 06:03.196
<i>had his makeshift family feeling on edge.</i>

06:03.654 --> 06:05.740
Oh, I can go downstairs,
maybe go to a store.

06:05.823 --> 06:07.825
No! I'm the provider for this family.

06:07.909 --> 06:09.535
If anyone gets to leave, it's me.

06:09.619 --> 06:11.746
Yeah, you're good at that, Dad.
You're good at leaving.

06:11.829 --> 06:13.498
It... It's kind of your thing, actually.

06:13.873 --> 06:16.250
Hey, I don't have to crouch here
for this... Ow!

06:16.334 --> 06:18.169
I just don't understand
why we're still here.

06:18.252 --> 06:19.462
- Shh!
- Why are we hiding?

06:19.545 --> 06:22.465
Yeah, I thought you said
you were the sticky white glue

06:22.548 --> 06:24.634
that this family sniffs together.

06:24.717 --> 06:26.552
All right, look,
we're in a bad situation here.

06:27.261 --> 06:28.554
But, I've been jammed

06:28.638 --> 06:30.932
with bigger things
in tighter spots than this.

06:31.015 --> 06:31.933
Ah.

06:32.016 --> 06:34.102
We just need better living conditions.

06:36.062 --> 06:37.814
Isn't that what the Bluth Company does?

06:37.897 --> 06:39.816
No, you fuck... Oh!

06:40.066 --> 06:41.609
- Mmm...
- Uh-huh, uh-huh.

06:41.692 --> 06:42.819
- Mm-hmm.
- Uh-huh.

06:42.902 --> 06:45.822
<i>Oscar and Buster, meanwhile,</i>
<i>had found a new place to live.</i>

06:45.905 --> 06:46.864
<i>This is a great pad.</i>

06:46.948 --> 06:49.534
I know.
This is what we in the Bluth family

06:49.617 --> 06:52.412
call a "Don't Tell Michael."

06:52.495 --> 06:54.539
<i>But their new roommate wanted out.</i>

06:54.789 --> 06:56.249
Maybe I'll go make us some popcorn.

06:56.332 --> 06:58.501
Oh. Are we gonna go in the kitchen?

06:58.584 --> 07:01.003
We're gonna, I don't know,
boil some hot oil?

07:01.087 --> 07:04.215
Nice try, bitch.

07:04.298 --> 07:06.384
Yeah, nice try, B.

07:06.676 --> 07:10.555
- I'd love some popcorn, please.
- Hey, smart guy.

07:10.638 --> 07:12.014
Can we watch a movie,

07:12.098 --> 07:14.684
or just leave the lights on
so we can't see you?

07:14.767 --> 07:17.728
We can stay up late if you want
and watch it, or something.

07:17.812 --> 07:20.148
Thanks for dinner, Annette.

07:20.231 --> 07:24.152
- See you next time, Bev.
- I thought you said you lived here alone.

07:24.235 --> 07:25.987
It's my old lady.
Leave her out of it, please?

07:26.070 --> 07:27.488
She's a very sweet person.

07:27.572 --> 07:29.782
She's smiling all the time,
even when she sleeps.

07:29.866 --> 07:31.033
I always get the wrong key.

07:31.117 --> 07:32.910
- On my cue, rising.
- Mm...

07:34.996 --> 07:36.998
And in three, two, one.

07:37.123 --> 07:41.043
Inside, outside.
Inside, outside. Inside, outside.

07:41.127 --> 07:43.171
Outside. Inside, outside.

07:43.254 --> 07:46.549
- You blow our cover, and she's a goner.
- Inside, outside.

07:50.011 --> 07:51.179
Run, Annette, run!

07:51.262 --> 07:53.598
Maeby? Why'd he call you Annette?

07:53.681 --> 07:55.808
Huh?

07:57.894 --> 07:58.895
Hand.

07:58.978 --> 08:01.272
Inside, outside. Inside, outside.

08:01.481 --> 08:03.399
And this is why I told you
to buy the safety hair.

08:03.483 --> 08:06.110
<i>While Maeby was hoping</i>
<i>to erase memories...</i>

08:06.194 --> 08:08.154
Now I gotta drink the evidence.

08:08.237 --> 08:11.491
<i>...back at the model home,
Michael was bonding with his son.</i>

08:11.574 --> 08:14.035
You know?
You're dating the girl of my dreams.

08:14.118 --> 08:15.953
Your dreams. You know?

08:16.037 --> 08:17.997
What I meant was,
my dreams are your dreams.

08:18.372 --> 08:20.625
Have you ever noticed that dreams are hard
to remember?

08:20.708 --> 08:22.126
There's one I can't forget.

08:22.210 --> 08:24.170
The dream of us working together.
Do you remember

08:24.253 --> 08:27.089
how we wanted to make sure
we could hang out all day every day?

08:27.340 --> 08:29.091
- Like you and your dad.
- That was not a dream.

08:29.175 --> 08:30.968
Think I wanted to hang out with my father?

08:31.052 --> 08:33.554
That was a job.
No, but listen, I want you to know

08:33.638 --> 08:35.847
that I'm available to you 24 hours a day,

08:35.932 --> 08:37.892
any time you want,
to talk about business.

08:37.975 --> 08:39.727
And don't think
I can't handle the tech stuff.

08:39.808 --> 08:42.063
I spent those five and a half weeks
up at the Search campus.

08:42.145 --> 08:43.856
I'm texting with one hand,
you've seen that.

08:43.940 --> 08:45.942
Well,
my problems are not that easily solved.

08:46.025 --> 08:48.152
- Oh, yeah?
- Turns out, we're way more in debt

08:48.236 --> 08:49.570
than I thought we were.

08:49.820 --> 08:51.113
- Same here.
- Yeah.

08:51.489 --> 08:53.449
I... I'm suddenly running
the Bluth Company,

08:53.533 --> 08:55.284
and they're up to something.
I don't know what it is,

08:55.368 --> 08:56.285
but we're broke.

08:56.452 --> 08:58.454
It's just, these offices
are just wiping us out.

08:58.538 --> 09:01.457
And same here.
Gob's got us on two floors now.

09:01.541 --> 09:04.418
Trying to get my employees to describe
what they're doing is like pulling teeth.

09:04.502 --> 09:06.546
I think there are
a couple of Two Hour Teeth guys

09:06.629 --> 09:10.091
still on the payroll. No one will confirm,
but I'm convinced that in the break room,

09:10.174 --> 09:12.426
there's still an active chair.
Anyway, despite all of this,

09:12.510 --> 09:14.929
you and I are gonna get through this.
You want to know why?

09:15.179 --> 09:16.847
The Bluth boys, we find a way.

09:16.931 --> 09:18.724
- We're winners.
- Agreed.

09:19.850 --> 09:22.228
Hey, so, non sequitur,
what do you know about bankruptcy?

09:22.478 --> 09:25.356
You know, I was just checking
into that. No, look.

09:25.439 --> 09:26.857
I don't know what else I can do.

09:26.941 --> 09:29.735
Dad said go in there
and save the company, find money.

09:29.819 --> 09:32.488
But despite all their shady bookkeeping,
there's nothing left.

09:32.572 --> 09:34.532
There's just... there's Sudden Valley.
That's it.

09:34.615 --> 09:36.659
The one thing that was mine.
Well, and whatever's

09:36.742 --> 09:39.996
in that file, that "Gated Community,"
but... but you're different.

09:40.371 --> 09:41.414
You're right at the beginning.

09:41.497 --> 09:45.042
You shouldn't be thinking
about bankruptcy at all, you know?

09:45.585 --> 09:47.295
Can't you get a loan?

09:47.503 --> 09:51.591
Well, I mean, Rebel offered
to buy the whole company outright.

09:51.674 --> 09:53.509
- Oh, you can't do that.
- No. I mean...

09:53.593 --> 09:55.469
- Forget about that.
- What if the software...

09:55.553 --> 09:57.179
- Is worth billions?
- ...never works?

09:58.514 --> 09:59.432
It doesn't seem likely.

09:59.515 --> 10:02.393
- These expenses are just killing us.
- Hey, hang on.

10:02.935 --> 10:05.688
Uh, I think I got a solution
for both of us.

10:09.108 --> 10:12.361
- And... open your eyes.
- Was I supposed to close them?

10:13.029 --> 10:14.739
Hmm? Oh, yeah. Well, anyway,

10:14.822 --> 10:16.866
these are the offices.
What do you think?

10:16.949 --> 10:18.868
Oh, 'cause you're
on the fourth floor now. I...

10:18.951 --> 10:21.579
Yeah, you set up Fakeblock here.
It's free rent.

10:22.163 --> 10:24.248
I don't know, I mean, you know,
this was your office.

10:24.332 --> 10:25.416
This was where you were president.

10:26.083 --> 10:28.628
Where decisions were made that you...

10:28.711 --> 10:30.171
Eventually found out about.

10:30.254 --> 10:32.298
But... but, look, you know,
this was our dream, right?

10:32.381 --> 10:33.758
To work together? Do you remember

10:33.841 --> 10:35.384
- all the dreaming we did?
- Yeah.

10:35.468 --> 10:37.094
Have lunch together.
Work out in the late afternoon.

10:37.178 --> 10:38.679
That's right,
we were gonna put a weight room

10:38.763 --> 10:40.139
- in the back office.
- You know it, yeah.

10:40.222 --> 10:42.308
Drive home together,
shower up, grab dinner,

10:42.391 --> 10:44.560
- PJs on, teeth brushed.
- A little TV.

10:44.644 --> 10:47.563
A little bit of TV, sure,
and then a little kiss good night

10:47.647 --> 10:49.690
and off to bed.
You know, I am just realizing

10:49.774 --> 10:51.651
that I'm still picturing you
as a ten-year-old.

10:51.734 --> 10:53.194
I think I was trying to engineer

10:53.277 --> 10:55.655
a way to stay up late
and watch <i>The Tom Green Show.</i>

10:55.738 --> 10:57.573
Mm, yeah, see,
I don't get the new guys.

10:57.657 --> 10:59.617
Anyway, it can be a new dream,
then, you know?

10:59.700 --> 11:02.953
I'll be able to come here all the time.
You'll be able to pop up whenever.

11:03.454 --> 11:05.122
I'm not sure it's a good idea, you know?

11:05.206 --> 11:06.707
- Yeah.
- I'm feeling anxious as it is.

11:06.791 --> 11:08.793
This is just gonna be great, isn't it?

11:08.876 --> 11:10.336
It's gonna be so much fun!

11:10.419 --> 11:14.090
<i>George Michael wasn't the only one</i>
<i>who felt shackled to his father.</i>

11:14.173 --> 11:16.425
Inside,
outside, inside, outside,

11:16.509 --> 11:18.052
inside, outside, inside...

11:18.135 --> 11:19.845
- Hello.
- Oh, no.

11:19.929 --> 11:22.765
- Ew!
- Waving with righty. We've discussed this.

11:22.848 --> 11:24.183
- Sorry.
- There's gotta be a way

11:24.266 --> 11:27.144
we can cover more ground
without attracting attention.

11:27.520 --> 11:30.231
Oh, I've got the perfect idea for that.

11:33.442 --> 11:36.529
Wet side, dry side,
wet side, dry side, wet side, dry side...

11:36.612 --> 11:38.406
Okay.

11:38.489 --> 11:40.282
Are you all right?

11:40.366 --> 11:41.951
We should have taken
the tandem bike.

11:42.034 --> 11:43.703
Nah.
Never would have fit in here.

11:43.786 --> 11:45.871
Oh, I see what you mean.

11:47.623 --> 11:49.542
<i>George Michael</i>
<i>was showing his cousin</i>

